%md #Overview: Graph Algorithm to-date in SciSpark This notebook will demonstrate using SciSpark to: * read in netCDF files * mask areas in an array meeting a criteria * connect these areas via overlap between two time steps to form a graph object. * Search this graph object to find subgraphs meeting a minimum length criteria * Visualization These are all the steps conducted to identify and track mesoscale convective systems (MCSs) as outlined in Whitehall et al. 2014. ![The major steps of the GTG](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SciSpark/scispark_zeppelin_notebooks/master/images/GTGSteps.png) Figure 1: The major steps of the the Grab 'em, Tag 'em, Graph 'em algorithm For this demonstration, hrly brightness temperature NCEP/CPC MERG dataset over location 5S - 40N, 60E - 90W is used. More information about the NCEP/CPC 4km MERG Dataset used for this demonstration can be found [here] (http://mirador.gsfc.nasa.gov/collections/MERG__001.shtml).
####Useful references * Palamuttam, R., R. Marroquín Mogrovejo, C. Mattmann, B. Wilson, K. Whitehall, R. Verma, L. McGibbney, and P. Ramirez, 2015. SciSpark: Applying In-memory Distributed Computing to Weather Event Detection and Tracking. In 2015 IEEE International Conference on Big Data (Big Data) on, pp. 1959 - 1965. * Whitehall, K., C. Mattmann, G. Jenkins, M. Rwebangira, B. Demoz, D. Waliser, J. Kim, C. Goodale, A. Hart, P. Ramirez, M. Joyce, M. Boustani, P. Zimdars, P. Loikith, and H. Lee, 2014. Exploring a graph theory based algorithm for automated identification and characterization of large mesoscale convective systems in satellite datasets. Earth Science Informatics. DOI: 10.1007/s12145-014-0181-3 () Note that in the nomenclature used in this notebook, a *frame* indicates the date and time associated with a netCDF file.

Overview: Graph Algorithm to-date in SciSpark

This notebook will demonstrate using SciSpark to:

  • read in netCDF files
  • mask areas in an array meeting a criteria
  • connect these areas via overlap between two time steps to form a graph object.
  • Search this graph object to find subgraphs meeting a minimum length criteria
  • Visualization
    These are all the steps conducted to identify and track mesoscale convective systems (MCSs) as outlined in Whitehall et al. 2014.

           Figure 1: The major steps of the the Grab 'em, Tag 'em, Graph 'em algorithm

For this demonstration, hrly brightness temperature NCEP/CPC MERG dataset over location 5S - 40N, 60E - 90W is used. More information about the NCEP/CPC 4km MERG Dataset used for this demonstration can be found here.

Useful references

  • Palamuttam, R., R. Marroquín Mogrovejo, C. Mattmann, B. Wilson, K. Whitehall, R. Verma, L. McGibbney, and P. Ramirez, 2015. SciSpark: Applying In-memory Distributed Computing to Weather Event Detection and Tracking. In 2015 IEEE International Conference on Big Data (Big Data) on, pp. 1959 - 1965.

  • Whitehall, K., C. Mattmann, G. Jenkins, M. Rwebangira, B. Demoz, D. Waliser, J. Kim, C. Goodale, A. Hart, P. Ramirez, M. Joyce, M. Boustani, P. Zimdars, P. Loikith, and H. Lee, 2014. Exploring a graph theory based algorithm for automated identification and characterization of large mesoscale convective systems in satellite datasets. Earth Science Informatics. DOI: 10.1007/s12145-014-0181-3 ()

Note that in the nomenclature used in this notebook, a frame indicates the date and time associated with a netCDF file.

%md
## Find cloud elements and connect the cloud elements between frames
*Cloud elements* are defined as contiguous regions where the temperature is atleast 241.0K and an area is met. 241K is a reasonable brightness temperature threshold for deep convection in detection in the Tropics (Machado et al. 1998).

In order to observe features are forming over time, it is necessary to connect *cloud elements* between *frames*. The connection, referred to as an *edge*, is created between *cloud elements* of consecutive *frames* if: 
* the area between consecutive frames is >= 2400.00 squared_km
OR
* the area between consecutive frames is < 2400.00 squared_km and the convective fraction is < 0.9. The convective fraction is defined as the ratio of minimum to maximum brightness temperature

![Finding cloud elements](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SciSpark/scispark_zeppelin_notebooks/master/images/sRDDtimeSeq.png)                          
               Figure 2: Illustration of how the cloud elements and edges are determined

This algorithm was originally developed for use in West Africa. As such, this criteria follows discussions in the literature about the microphysical characterization of MCS features in the area of interest and previous temperature threshold implementations (Bouniol et al. 2010, Machado et al. 1993, Mapes and Houze 1993, Goyens et al. 2011)

At the end of this step, a sparely connected graph representing the  cloud elements found and their connectivity through out the user defined datasets. 

Notice the **sciTensor** is being passed around and manipulated.

paragraphs.title: Write EdgeList and Nodes to files
paragraphs.text:
def updateLatLons(node: MCCNode): MCCNode = {
    val props:mutable.HashMap[String, Double] = node.metadata.get("properties")
      .getOrElse().asInstanceOf[mutable.HashMap[String, Double]]
    val xMax = props.get("rowMax").get
    val xMin = props.get("rowMin").get
    val yMax = props.get("colMax").get
    val yMin = props.get("colMin").get

    val latMax = lat(xMax.toInt)
    val latMin = lat(xMin.toInt)
    val lonMin = lon(yMin.toInt)
    val lonMax = lon(yMax.toInt)
    val centerLat = (latMax+latMin)/2
    val centerLon = (lonMax+lonMin)/2

    props += (("latMin", latMin))
    props += (("latMax", latMax))
    props += (("lonMin", lonMin))
    props += (("lonMax", lonMax))
    props += (("centerLat", centerLat))
    props += (("centerLon", centerLon))
     
    return node
}


val MCCNodeMap = new mutable.HashMap[String, MCCNode]()
val componentFrameRDD_collected = componentFrameRDD1n.collect()
componentFrameRDD_collected.foreach{edge => {
  val srcKey = s"${edge.srcNode.frameNum},${edge.srcNode.cloudElemNum}"
  val destKey = s"${edge.destNode.frameNum},${edge.destNode.cloudElemNum}"
  
  if (!MCCNodeMap.contains(srcKey)){
    updateLatLons(edge.srcNode)
    MCCNodeMap += ((srcKey, edge.srcNode))
    }
    if (!MCCNodeMap.contains(destKey)) {
        updateLatLons(edge.destNode)
    MCCNodeMap += ((destKey, edge.destNode))
    }
}}
val pw = new PrintWriter("MCCNodesLines.json")
MCCNodeMap.foreach{ case (key, value) => {
    pw.write(value.toString)
    pw.write("\n")
}}
pw.close()

val MCCEdgeList = componentFrameRDD_collected.toList
val fw = new java.io.FileWriter(new File("MCCEdges.txt"))
fw.write(MCCEdgeList.toString())
fw.close()
